            "comments": [
                {
                    "file": "/PATCHSET_LEVEL",
                    "line": 0,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Jeremy Kerr",
                        "email": "jk@ozlabs.org",
                        "username": "jk-ozlabs"
                    },
                    "message": "Overall concept LGTM, just a minor clarification on the implementation."
                },
                {
                    "file": "console-server.c",
                    "line": 436,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Jeremy Kerr",
                        "email": "jk@ozlabs.org",
                        "username": "jk-ozlabs"
                    },
                    "message": "in this case, you'll want to free any allocated sink/source/path buffers; maybe move the `out_free_glob` label to before those `free()`s ?"
                },
                {
                    "file": "console-server.c",
                    "line": 436,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Zev Weiss",
                        "email": "zev@bewilderbeest.net",
                        "username": "zevweiss"
                    },
                    "message": "Yeah, the only problem then being that if we take the earlier `goto` then we'd be free()-ing uninitialized pointers -- adding a second label before the free() calls and jumping to that instead should address both problems though I think."
                },
                {
                    "file": "console-server.c",
                    "line": 436,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Jeremy Kerr",
                        "email": "jk@ozlabs.org",
                        "username": "jk-ozlabs"
                    },
                    "message": "Or just initialise to NULL, with `free(NULL)` being a nop."
                },
                {
                    "file": "console-server.c",
                    "line": 436,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Zev Weiss",
                        "email": "zev@bewilderbeest.net",
                        "username": "zevweiss"
                    },
                    "message": "Done"
                },
                {
                    "file": "console-server.c",
                    "line": 443,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Jeremy Kerr",
                        "email": "jk@ozlabs.org",
                        "username": "jk-ozlabs"
                    },
                    "message": "Maybe add `/` to the disallowed chars in `sink`? Or check for this separately?\n\n[`aspeed-uart-routing = ../../../../../../etc/passwd:foo` ?]"
                },
                {
                    "file": "console-server.c",
                    "line": 443,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Zev Weiss",
                        "email": "zev@bewilderbeest.net",
                        "username": "zevweiss"
                    },
                    "message": "Ooh, nice exploit haha!  Yeah, that'd be good to prevent; adding `/` should be an easy fix I think."
                },
                {
                    "file": "console-server.c",
                    "line": 443,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Zev Weiss",
                        "email": "zev@bewilderbeest.net",
                        "username": "zevweiss"
                    },
                    "message": "Actually, maybe we should just enforce that it matches `/^(io|uart)/`, since there are other writable files in that directory (e.g. `uevent` and `driver_override`) that we wouldn't want it touching either..."
                },
                {
                    "file": "console-server.c",
                    "line": 443,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Jeremy Kerr",
                        "email": "jk@ozlabs.org",
                        "username": "jk-ozlabs"
                    },
                    "message": "> Actually, maybe we should just enforce that it matches `/^(io|uart)/`\n\nYeah, good point; an explicit match sounds good."
                },
                {
                    "file": "console-server.c",
                    "line": 443,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Zev Weiss",
                        "email": "zev@bewilderbeest.net",
                        "username": "zevweiss"
                    },
                    "message": "Done"
                },
                {
                    "file": "console-server.c",
                    "line": 453,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Jeremy Kerr",
                        "email": "jk@ozlabs.org",
                        "username": "jk-ozlabs"
                    },
                    "message": "I admire that you're conserving lines of code here \ud83d\ude0a however, this could be more clear with a bit of expansion.\n\n(and it doesn't fclose() if the fprintf fails? Are you relying on the implementation of `fprintf` to only hit the `FILE *` buffer, and the sysfs ->store error being reported by `fclose()` ?)"
                },
                {
                    "file": "console-server.c",
                    "line": 453,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Zev Weiss",
                        "email": "zev@bewilderbeest.net",
                        "username": "zevweiss"
                    },
                    "message": "Haha...the aim was more deduplication of the error-handling code than concision (and IMO it was significantly more readable in its original one-expression-per-line form in patchset 1 before reformatting to appease the CI checks), but yeah, I suppose it does also have the no-close-on-write-error problem (even though as you point out it _might_ technically be able to get away with it, especially omitting the linefeed as a concession to compatibility with kernels predating [this patch](https://lore.kernel.org/lkml/20230628083735.19946-2-zev@bewilderbeest.net/), but that certainly wasn't the intent)...I'll redo it a bit less tersely."
                },
                {
                    "file": "console-server.c",
                    "line": 453,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Zev Weiss",
                        "email": "zev@bewilderbeest.net",
                        "username": "zevweiss"
                    },
                    "message": "Alright, I cobbled together a sequence that tries to be slightly more readable & correct while still avoiding duplicating the error message for all three calls...it's maybe slightly unusual-looking but not awful I think?"
                },
                {
                    "file": "console-server.c",
                    "line": 453,
                    "reviewer": {
                        "name": "Zev Weiss",
                        "email": "zev@bewilderbeest.net",
                        "username": "zevweiss"
                    },
                    "message": "...and of course now I realize adding a little helper function instead makes this a lot easier."
                }
